I have taken the dataset from the UCI machine learning respository, with following website: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/144/statlog+german+credit+data. The data contains fincancial infromation associated with a thousand clients and labels them as good or bad credit. The purpose of this assignment is to best classify a client, based on his/her financial history, as a good or a bad one. We note that, as mentioned on the above website, it is more imnportant for the bank to classify a bad credit than a good one.

We can see that the response data is distributed between 1 and 2, representing good and the bad credit, respectively. We note a few things about the response variable:
  • Since there are only two labels, it is a binary classification issue.
  • The response is unevenly distributed between 1 and 2, i.e., good and bad risk, which is in the ratio of 70 to 30, respectively. In this case, even if a classifier classifies all the points as 1, i.e., good credit risk, the accuracy will be 0.7, which is not helpful. For the current purpose, we need to be able to classify the bad credit risk as efficiently as possible, which is in the minority. Therefore, we will need other metrics like recall, precision, and f1 scores, instead of accuracy to benchmark our models.

Preparing data for modeling¶

In [12]:
# checking the shape of the data
print('shape of the data: ', X.shape)
print('shape of the response data: ', y.shape)

shape of the data:  (1000, 20)
shape of the response data:  (1000, 1)
A few points to note:
  • As shown above, the response is distributed between 1 and 2, i.e, good and bad risk However, SkLearn classifiers are designed by default to consider 0 as negative and 1 as positive. So, we will change the response values to this format, i.e., 0 representing a good credit and 1, a bad one.
  • To perform classification based on columns with categorical values, we will have to convert them to an appropriate format, where we will create additional columns based on the categories within a column.
  • Some of the algorithms that we will use benefit from scaling of the features, viz., Logistic regression, K-Nearest Neighbour, Support vector machines. Other algorithms — Decision-Tree based — are not affected by the standardization, viz., Adaboost, Random Forest, and GradientDescent using Decsion-Trees as respective classifiers. Since standardization does not negatively impact any of the algorithms, we will perform standardization of the feature columns, i.e, X dataset, for all classification models to avoid going back and forth between two different datasets.
In the below section, we perform all the above modifications:
In [3]:
# Flattening the response data
y = np.ravel(y)
# Changing the range of data from {1,2} to {0, 1}, which better suits the bformat of binary classification of sklearn library
y = [val-1 for val in y]

# creating dummy columns from the categories in the categorical columns
X = pd.get_dummies(X, drop_first= True)

X_test = sc.fit_transform(X_test)

Modeling¶

Before delving into the modelling, I will discuss my strategy. I will consider multiple supervised learning classification algorithms to classify the data, tuning their hyperparameters to get the best model. The tuning strategy will depend on various metrics, including accuracy, precision, recall, f1 score, and area under the precision-recall curve. Since the dataset is skewed with only 30% of positive labels, i.e., bad credits, and it is more critical to identify bad credits compared to good ones, my primary emphasis will be on recall while also paying due attention to precision, f1 scores, and area under the precision-recall curve. Accuracy will not be a significant concern here — as mentioned earlier, it is very easy to get 70% accuracy by classifying everyone as a good credit risk, but it will fail our cause by incorrectly identifying all the bad risks. Similarly, ROC curve will not be part of our metrics, as it is not an optimal indicator with skewed data, instead we will use the precision-recall curve. Nevertheless, we will check accuracy scores to ensure our model isn’t doing anything funny. Finally, we will compare different models to find the best one(s) for the present purpose.

Nearest Neighbor¶

In [17]:
allks = range(1,40)
def computeknn(k):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors= k).fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    return accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred), precision_score(y_test, y_pred), recall_score(y_test, y_pred), \
    f1_score(np.ravel(y_test), y_pred)
    
scores = [computeknn(k) for k in allks]

def extract_scores(n, scores = scores):
    return list(map(lambda x: x[n], scores))

accuracy = extract_scores(0)
precision = extract_scores(1)
recall = extract_scores(2)
f1score = extract_scores(3)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1,figsize=(6,5))
ax.plot(allks, accuracy, marker="o", color="steelblue", lw=1, label="accuracy")
ax.plot(allks, precision, marker="o", color="darkred", lw=1, label="precision")
ax.plot(allks, recall, marker="o", color="darkgreen", lw=1, label="recall")
ax.plot(allks, f1score, marker="o", color="purple", lw=1, label="f1score")
ax.set_xlabel("number neighbors", fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("accuracy", fontsize=14)
ax.grid(alpha=0.25)
ax.set_title('Scores on the test data set by changing the number of nearest neighbors')
ax.legend()

<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x2c132a5f920>

The above plots show accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 scores as we prune the tree. We can see that the respective scores on the training data set decrease as we prune the tree, i.e., removing entries with low ccp_alpha values. In constrast, the respective scores on the test data set remain almost unchanged or increase slightly.
Based on the above plots and considering the importance of recall and f1 scores for this dataset, pruning upto the level of ccp_alpha = 0.003 gives the optimal scores, shown above.

def getpredict(ntrees):
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators= ntrees, random_state= 0).fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)
    return clf.score(X_train, y_train), clf.score(X_test, y_test), precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train),\
    precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test), recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train), recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test),\
    f1_score(y_train, y_pred_train), f1_score(y_test, y_pred_test)

scores = list(map(getpredict, range(1, 100)))

accuracy_train, accuracy_test, precision_train, precision_test, recall_train, recall_test, f1_train, f1_test = zip(*scores)

Conclusion¶

Below, I provide a table listing the scores on the test dataset from all the classifiers we analyzed in this notebook.
Classifier Accuracy Precison Recall F1 score AUC
Logistic Classification using 'lbfgs' solver 0.705 0.494 0.672 0.569 0.527
K-Nearest Neighbors 0.695 0.471 0.414 0.44 0.479
Decision Tree Classifier with pruning 0.75 0.58 0.5 0.537 0.502
Random Forest 0.77 0.658 0.431 0.521 0.563
Ada Boost 0.74 0.548 0.586 0.567 0.49
Gradient Boosting 0.785 0.66 0.534 0.59 0.653
SVM - linear Kernel 0.73 0.538 0.483 0.509 0.482
SVM - rbf Kernel 0.735 0.551 0.466 0.505 Computationally expensive
Since, in the current project, we are more concerned with identifying the bad credits and the dataset is skewed with 70-30 ratio of good vs bad credit risks, we are much more interested in recall, which tells us the number of true positives detected out of all the actual positives.
Precision is also important, as it tells us the ratio of correctly classified positives to all the classified positives. However, for the present dataset, the source link mentions that it is much more desirable to avoid classifying a bad risk as a good one than vice versa. Therefore, it makes recall more important than the precision. Nevertheless, precision is an important quantity for the present data, as it is still desirable to avoid classifying good ones as bad credit risks. Hence, for our project, we will make two conclusions, one based solely on recall, and the other based on the F1 score, which is a harmonic mean of recall and precision.

Based on recall, the above table clearly shows that the Logistic regression is the winner. As far as f1 scores are concerned, Logistic regression is still the best one; however, other classifiers like Random Forest, Gradient boost, and Ada Boost also provide almost similar performance based on the f1 scores, and slight mismatches among their values could possibly be from sampling of the test dataset. Besides, to the extent area under the precision-recall curve is concerned, the results follow the same conclusion as that based on recall and f1 scores. However, the gradient boost algorithm provides a clear advantage over the other methods.
